if you have set image_data_format=channels_last, then any model loaded from this repository will get built according to the TensorFlow data format convention, "Height-Width-Depth".

This is the case in our config.

Data preprocessing¶

The input images fed into the model must be of size (224, 224) and the model will return a same-sized mask. So to train our model, we must resize and preprocess our training data (real images and labeled images).

We add a transformation function that randomly transforms the image (and the corresponding mask) by:

  • cropping
  • horizontal flip
  • rotation +/- 15
  • modifying brightness and contrast
  • add motion blur,
    with a probability of 0.5.
In [ ]:
class ImageTransformer():
    def __init__(self):
        self._transform = A.Compose([
            A.RandomSizedCrop(min_max_height=(244, 1024), width=512, height=512, p=0.5),
            A.HorizontalFlip(p=0.5),
            A.Rotate(limit=15, p=0.5),
            A.RandomBrightnessContrast(p=0.5),
            A.MotionBlur(p=0.5)
        ])

    def transform_image_and_mask(self, img, mask):
        '''
        Return transformed img and mask after random transformation
        (see self.transform : crop, horizontal fil, brightness, contrast.)
        '''
        transformed = self._transform(image=img, mask=mask)
        return transformed['image'], transformed['mask']

We also create a data generator that will yield batches of images and their corresponding masks, randomly transformed.

In [ ]:
class BatchedDataGenerator():
    """
    Yield preprocessed images and masks ready to feed the model.
    Parameters:
    
    - batch_size: as its name suggests
    - image_size: requested size to feed the model
    - imgs_names: list of images names (names must be the same in imgs dir and masks dir)
    - imgs_dir, masks_dirs: where to find corresponding images with imgs names.
    """
    def __init__(self, batch_size, image_size, imgs_names, imgs_dir, masks_dir):
        self.batch_size = batch_size
        self.image_size = image_size
        self.imgs_names = imgs_names
        self.imgs_dir = imgs_dir
        self.masks_dir = masks_dir
        self.transform = ImageTransformer().transform_image_and_mask
        self.preprocess_input = preprocess_input
          
    def augmented_and_processed_img_and_mask_for(self, name, augment=True):
        """
        Return a tuple of Tensors (preprocessed image, preprocessed mask)
        for image and mask named <name> (found respectively in self.imgs_dir
        and self.masks_dir).
        If augment = True, image and mask are randomly augmented
        (crop, horizontal flip, brightness, contrast), else they are left unchanged,
        then :
        - image is preprocessed as required by ResNet50 model
        - each class pixel in mask is one-hot-encoded
        Eventually, image and mask are resized to the input size required
        by ResNet50 input layer.
        """
        img_name = self.imgs_dir + name
        mask_name = self.masks_dir + name

        img = tf.io.read_file(img_name)
        img = tf.io.decode_png(img)
        img = img.numpy()

        mask = tf.io.read_file(mask_name)
        mask = tf.io.decode_png(mask)
        mask = mask.numpy()

        # Optionally apply augmentation to img and mask
        transformed_img, transformed_mask = img, mask
        if augment:
            transformed_img, transformed_mask = self.transform(img, mask)

        # Preprocess according to model requirements
        preprocessed_img = self.preprocess_input(transformed_img)
        ohe_mask = tf.squeeze(tf.one_hot(transformed_mask, depth=NB_CLASSES))
        
        # Resize image and mask
        resized_img = tf.image.resize(preprocessed_img, image_size)
        resized_mask = tf.image.resize(ohe_mask, image_size)

        return resized_img, resized_mask

    def batch_generator(self, augment):
        '''
        Infinite generator.
        Return tuple of tensors ([self.batch_size, img_witdh, img_height, ...]) of
        augmented and preprocessed images and masks based on self.imgs_names list.
        '''
        while True:
            shuffled_list = self.imgs_names.copy()
            random.shuffle(shuffled_list)

            for i in range(0, len(shuffled_list) - batch_size, batch_size):
                names_batch = shuffled_list[i: i+ batch_size]
                imgs = []
                masks = []
                for name in names_batch:
                    img, mask = self.augmented_and_processed_img_and_mask_for(name, augment)
                    imgs.append(img)
                    masks.append(mask)
                imgs = tf.convert_to_tensor(imgs)
                masks = tf.convert_to_tensor(masks)
                yield (imgs, masks)

Thaks to this class we create the generators we need to train and validate results of the model. Validation and test data will not be augmented.

Create custom model from ResNet50¶

This model is trained on image classification, so we cannot use it directly for semantic segmentation. But we can reuse its convolutional layers to build a Unet model and perform image segmentation.

We build a Unet model where the output of each convolutional layer is concatenated to that of the corresponding decoder (Convolutional transpose) layer.

In [ ]:
def conv_block(input_, num_filters):
    x = Conv2D(num_filters, 3, padding="same")(input_)
    x = BatchNormalization()(x)
    x = Activation("relu")(x)

    x = Conv2D(num_filters, 3, padding="same")(x)
    x = BatchNormalization()(x)
    x = Activation("relu")(x)

    return x

def decoder_block(input_, skip_features, num_filters):
    x = Conv2DTranspose(num_filters, (2, 2), strides=2, padding="same")(input_)
    x = Concatenate()([x, skip_features])
    x = conv_block(x, num_filters)
    return x

def build_resnet50_unet(input_shape, num_classes, adam_initial_lr=1e-1):
    inputs = Input(input_shape)
    resnet50 = ResNet50(include_top=False, weights="imagenet", input_tensor=inputs)
    resnet50.trainable = False

    # Encoder 
    s1 = resnet50.get_layer(index=0).output           
    s2 = resnet50.get_layer("conv1_relu").output        
    s3 = resnet50.get_layer("conv2_block3_out").output  
    s4 = resnet50.get_layer("conv3_block4_out").output  

    # Bridge
    b1 = resnet50.get_layer("conv4_block6_out").output  

    # Decoder 
    d1 = decoder_block(b1, s4, 512)                     
    d2 = decoder_block(d1, s3, 256)                     
    d3 = decoder_block(d2, s2, 128)                     
    d4 = decoder_block(d3, s1, 64)                      

    # Output 
    outputs = Conv2D(num_classes, (1, 1),  padding="same",
                     activation='softmax')(d4)

    # Instantiation
    model = Model(inputs, outputs, name="ResNet50_U-Net")
    
    # Compilation
    lr_schedule = tf.keras.optimizers.schedules.ExponentialDecay(
    initial_learning_rate=adam_initial_lr,
    decay_steps=10000,
    decay_rate=0.9)

    optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=lr_schedule)
    model.compile(loss=CategoricalCrossentropy(),
                 optimizer=optimizer,
                 metrics = ['accuracy', OneHotMeanIoU(NB_CLASSES)],
                )
    return model

Predict with model¶

In [ ]:
def png_as_ndarray(img_path):
  '''Return png image as numpy ndarray.'''
  img = tf.io.read_file(img_path)
  img = tf.io.decode_png(img)
  img = img.numpy()
  return img

true_imgs_dir = drive_dir + 'Cityscapes/test/true_imgs/imgs/'
masks_dir = drive_dir + 'Cityscapes/test/labeled_imgs/imgs/'
samples_names = random.choices(test_names, k=5)

for img_name in samples_names:
  true_img = png_as_ndarray(true_imgs_dir + img_name)
  true_mask = png_as_ndarray(masks_dir + img_name)
  true_colored_mask = colorize(true_mask)


  # predict probabilities with model
  preprocessed_img = preprocess_input(true_img)
  preprocessed_img = tf.image.resize(preprocessed_img, image_size)
  preprocessed_img = tf.cast(preprocessed_img, tf.uint8)
  preprocessed_img = tf.expand_dims(preprocessed_img,0)
  predicted_prob = model.predict(preprocessed_img)[0]

  # select class with highest probability
  predicted_mask = tf.keras.backend.argmax(predicted_prob, axis=-1)
  predicted_colored_mask = colorize(predicted_mask.numpy().reshape((*image_size,1)))
  
  # resize image
  predicted_colored_mask = tf.image.resize(predicted_colored_mask, 
                                           (1024, 2048), method='nearest')

  # plot original, predicted and labeled images

  fig, axs = plt.subplots(1,3, figsize=(20,12))
  axs[0].imshow(true_img)
  axs[0].title.set_text('True image ' + img_name)
  axs[0].axis('off')
  axs[1].imshow(predicted_colored_mask)
  axs[1].title.set_text(f'Predicted mask')
  axs[1].axis('off');
  axs[2].imshow(true_colored_mask)
  axs[2].title.set_text('True mask')
  axs[2].axis('off')
  plt.show();
